deck_excerpt: Deck based in Shinobird Ritual monsters and Phantasm Spiral Archtype.
deck_description:
A build make to use token and normal monster as advantage to bring Shinobird Ritual monsters to the field and have an easy use of the Field Spell card Pacifs, The Phantasm City. The main idea of this deck is use Shinobird Baroness to swap 3 spell/trap on the opponent's field and bring Amano to your side of the field. The Spirit Monster Amano is an excellent way to stop hand traps since he will stay on the field after you end your turn. Baroness will give you 2 tokens, very usefull with Pacifics and Spiral Battle and Spiral Power on your hand. Spiral token can be used to tributo ritual both shinobird ritual monsters, as Phantasm Spiral Dragon can be sent to the Gy by Advencd Ritual spell card. Other solution to keep your side safe is to use Perfomapal Trump Witch's pendulum effect and Fusion summon your Normal Monster to bring First of the Dragons Fusion Monster to the field. As you can see, this deck is based to have at last one monster to stop your opponet to make a direct attack, or perform a otk. All cards on this recipe was used on a physical deck and YGOPRO deck as well. Very easy, very power, very fun Enjoy

deck_excerpt: Mekk-Knight Invoked Deck - Going 2nd - Mekk-Knight OTK - Invoked Disruption
deck_description:
The Deck is engineered around the speed and stun/negation of the Invoked Engine and the Swarm/OTK potential of Mekk-Knights. (You can run the wind witch engine + an extra Invoked Raidjin if you're interested in that, but my ideal combo is suited for a stronger shut down --> and better suited for the going second play style of Mekk-Knights.) *You always want to go second with this deck, no matter the case; having a Mekk-Knight in hand first turn is a complete brick --> and considering the number you're playing, you're almost always going to open with at least 1-3 cards in hand that would be a brick first turn (Handtraps/Mekk-Knights) A few custom choices one should consider with this deck:
  • Increasing Evenly Matched to 3
  • Reducing Indigo Eclipse to 2
  • Increasing Droll & Lock Bird to 3
  • Running Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit at 3
  • Running Effect Veiler at 3
  • Running 2 Raidjin
  • Running Mekk-Knight/World Legacy Spells & Traps (This helps if you're striving for a more pure/less interactive Mekk-Knight build, which I do not like)
True King of All Calamities Combo:
  • 0: This combo requires a Purple Nightfall or Azure Sky and an Aleister in hand (Magical Meltdown may suffice --> Adds an Aleister)
  • 1: SS Nightfall (set a spell/trap if you need to) to get an Azure or SS Azure to add a Mekk-Knight to hand (Whatever works for the situation; Nightfall to search if you haven't SSed Nightfall and activated it's eff already or an Indigo to make room/build up with other Mekk-Knights in hand)
    • Normal Aleister
      • Add Invocation to hand, don't activate
  • 2: Link Summon into Aleister the Meltdown Invoker
  • 3: Activate Invocation (Aleister + Azure in GY) for a Mechaba in one of the two zones of Aleister the Meltdown Invoker
    • Trigger Aleister MI and add an Invocation to hand by discarding one card in hand
    • Activate Invocation to recover Aleister + add Invocation back to the deck
  • 4: With the second invocation: Fuse the second Mekk-Knight you added off of Azure's eff (hopefully an Indigo Eclipse) with the Aleister added to the hand for a Second Mechaba
  • 5: Xyz into True King of All Calamities
  • 6: At this point, you can SS a third Mekk-Knight, go for a third Mechaba or another Invoked fusion monster (Raidjin is the second best in terms of stun/negation, but Purgatrio can help you push for game) depending on if you added invocation by Aleister MI's eff again or sit (because it's unlikely that you have anything; this would be a great time, however, to set a scapegoat).
Mekk-Knight Swarm:
  • 0: Purple in hand:
  • 1: SS Purple Nightfall to a column (setup if you have to/can)
  • 2: Add an Indigo or Azure (if you have an Azure in hand, add an indigo)
  • 3:
    • If you've added an Indigo and have an Azure in hand, then SS Indigo
      • Move Indigo
        • SS Azure, add Green/Red/Yellow (depends on what you're attempting to setup)
        • Link into Morning Star
          • Continue with whatever play you were thinking of (hopefully Aleister + Graveyard = Mechaba)
    • SS Azure and add Green/Red/Yellow/Indigo (depends on what you're attempting to setup)
      • If you've added Indigo (you should have a third Mekk-knight in hand if you're SSing Indigo)
        • Indigo Play: Move Indigo/Azure --> SS third Mekk-Knight into an open column
          • Game-End: Spectrum Supreme
          • Set-up: Morning Star (works well with Pure Mekk-Knights)
        • Non Indigo Play:
          • SS other Mekk Knight into a column where most usable (Red: pop a monster, Yellow: pop a spell)

deck_excerpt: The farthest I have gotten on trying to put together a pure-ish Diabolos beat-down/control deck that has toolbox characteristics.  Going-second geared
deck_description:
The goal of this is to practically shut down the game or beat up the opponent quickly depending on what happens early on.Note that the extra deck is a  work-in-progress and the side deck is not actually a side deck but just cards that I have thought about using/was using before.

Ideal Scenario Strategy

Ideally, the opponent sets up a board on turn 1.
  1. Then by some means (naturally draw, Terraforming, or Ahrima, King of Wickedness )  get 2 copies of Lair of Darkness in hand, get at least one to actually stay on the field (2 cards out of the starting 6).
  2. Next, tribute an opponent's monster to summon Duke Shade, King of the Umbra(card #3).
  3.  Then normal summon Ahrima (card #4),  and use it's effect to tribute Duke and search for the 2000 or more defense-criteria meeting Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair. Since the tribute for Ahrima went to your grave, you can summon Diabolos right off the search effect.
  4. At this point, you are left with 2 other cards in hand, with Ahrima and Diabolos on the board, allowing you to attack for potentially 4700 on turn 2. In main phase 2, tribute Ahrima with Diabolos to drain the opponents hand by 1 (of their choice) back to deck. Set whatever traps you have from cards #5 and 6. End the turn, get 3 1k/1k Torment Tokens in defense or watch Lair get hit by Ghost Ogre and Snow Rabbit. (they can not hit Lair with GO until it actively triggers in the end phase) This potentially will disrupt the opponent enough (especially if you have a virus available) that they either accomplish nothing the next turn, or they spend so many resources to reset the game state that they can not deal with your second Lair on turn #4.
Most of the time, you will be missing some piece of this combo, having a set monster on the opponents field which you can not tribute, or they will be able to Ash Blossom and Joyous Spring Ahrima's search when you did not have Lair or Diabolos in hand. Also, since you are going second, you will be vulnerable to counter traps like Solemn Strike. Other Notes on the main trick of the deck
  • Monster Reborn, if you have it, will allow you revive Ahrima after discarding it, and if you have Diabolos in hand or the grave, you can summon it right there by tributing Ahrima to draw rather than search (the latter options requires another monster as tribute). Alternatively, it can be used to grab a monster in the opponent's graveyard to be used as the Diabolos-summoning viable tribute target without costing the once-per-turn lair tribute, which can in turn be used for Diabolos's effect.
  • Lilith, Lady of Lament also works as a one-card means to summon Diabolos, but will cost you your normal summon (or MR if you somehow have her in the graveyard). She allows you grab traps like the viruses to make the big disruption play. The main issues with her include the telegraphed trap play of course, the fact that the effect is unusable once you are down to 2 normal traps in the deck, and that the one-card-play really denies you the ability to use the effect on your opponent's turn as a uninterruptible monster removal (In this deck Lilith, the viruses, and Dark Spirit Art-Greed are the only effects that allow you to do that on either turn).
  • Armageddon Knight works as another Foolish Burial, but costs you your normal summon. In that case, you would summon Diabolos via Duke tributing Armageddon.

Plan B: Stall it out

Given the strong presence of traps that are used in part to provide to Lilith with targets, even without the right offensive pieces, we can try to delay the game a bit so that we can get them. Our main stall monster is  Vijam, the Cubic Seed . It provides a set-able wall that will cost your opponent their monster's effects (and then you can just re-summon it from the spell and trap zone) or will continue to act as a non-battle destroy-able wall until your turn. Again this fits the theme of simply stalling the game out, but since we just set this, we can potentially avoid letting the opponent know what we are actually using until turn #4 (assuming we went second. Furthermore, it works as a target for Recurring Nightmare , which gives a +1 if and only if we have 2 or more monsters with 0 defense in the grave as targets (both Lilith and more importantly Ahrima fit that requirement) .
  • Scapeghost is also used as a stall card that more importantly advances our game state going into our next turn. 4x lvl 1 0/0 Zombie-type, Black Sheep tokens provides ample shielding against non-piercing boards. If they actually survive, we can use them to make Link Spiders, which we can turn around and use to make effect monster requiring links like Decode Talker. This card is much better if we have Linkuriboh available, although that is definitely will not be a budget friendly card until the next starter deck comes out in mid-July 2018. This could be used to make Firewall Dragon (again not the most cheap card at the moment, will come down assuming it gets reprinted as a tin promo) as well (although more often than not that one comes out from Lair's tokens).
  • Dark Hole/Raigeki (budget permitting) work(s) as a quick way(s) to clear a board(s), although both have a tendency to be ineffective if we actually have the tribute-engine online.
  • Mirror Force is of course the classic answer to attack defense. Can work well in conjunction with Scapeghost to keep it alive in order to flip it up and synchro-summon off it rather than just link-out with tokens.

Notes on the Other Cards Used

  • Malefic Stardust Dragon: Theoretically protects Lair of Darkness, but more often than not it is used as a stepping-stool for getting Diabolos out by being a valid tribute for it's summoning effect. Also can be used to make a rank 8 xyz with Diabolos like Hieratic Sun Dragon Overlord of Heliopolis .
  • Diabolos, King of the Abyss: The original version of Diabolos is costly to summon at two tributes (with no special summoning potential), but it will always generate valid tributes for darkest's summoning effect (because Lair does not give you tributes for tribute summons, it only gives the opponent tribute for effects). This one will not win a game for you, but it is a way to clinch a win out by selectively managing the opponent's draw phase while under the effects of a virus. Would be a lot better if it was 3k attack and level 8.
  • Soul Release: I generally like to include this card because it allows for grave managing offensively (banishing anything the opponent has in the grave that could be a target for something) or defensively (taking out grave-originating effects). Practically mandatory if GGV was used to take out any upside your opponent got out of it.
  • Dark Spirit Art - Greed : Allows for a really dirty way to abuse the viruses. All but GGV gives you hand information, meaning you know whether or not the opponent could even negate it, but with lair active it becomes even more nasty. I started using this instead of Share the Pain since it could be a Lilith target and I started to feel that Allure of Darkness tended to hurt me more than it helped, given I have no way of interacting with banished cards in this deck.
  • The Transmigration Prophecy : This one came out of a project to try to find a way to recycle destroyed lairs, as well as find more normal traps that were actually worth running (namely stuff other than battle traps and other situational traps that are hurt from the telegraphing so much). This ends up working somewhat like trap version of Soul Release, but I can also use it to recycle key cards that I have used up, namely lairs and particularly EEV.
  • Vampire Sucker Actually have not summoned this even once yet (in general I do not use the extra deck much with this). Mainly have it in there is as a highly situational means to draw possibly two cards off Scapeghost, one from summoning an opponent's monster by Sucker's effect, and then drawing for doing so, and then another from Formula Synchron. I could then tribute Sucker and the monster I summoned with sucker (by her own effect, not lair) into a Diabolos, darkest or original.

Diagnostic Manual Mk5

In order of severity.
  • Eradicator Epidemic Virus
    • Symptoms: Loss of Spell or Trap Capacities from the field or by drawing.
    • Notes: There is a reason this is the only one that is limited. Many decks require spell cards as either ways to draw or search for pieces of their combos, and in other cases killing traps simply clears the way for Diabolos to beat them into submission. Definitely the most common target for Lilith other than the triple bottomless search. Pretty easy to use with how common monsters with 2.5k+ attack are.
  • Full Force Virus
    • Symptoms: Loss of non-defensible (1500 or less) 'cells'. Can not take hold in non-defensive cells (Link monsters)
    • Notes: At first I was skeptical of using this card, but given how often Duke ended up sitting on the field (requires a 2k defense tribute like duke), it made for a good inclusion. This one actually manages to get a lot of monsters that people still use given how aggressive the game has become.
  • Deck Destruction Virus
    • Symptoms: Victimizes weak individuals (1500 or less atk), but effective against non-defensive hosts as well.
    • Notes: It is almost never an issue to find a target this (once Lair is up), but it really misses a lot of targets now. There are decks that use basically no monsters whatsoever that would be hit by this (Evilswarm, a deck where I used this as well, being one of them if the build does not run Evilswarm Obliviwisp). The one thing it can do well is of course is hit a bunch of weaker link monsters.
  • Grinning Grace Virus
    • Symptoms: Targets newborns (newly drawn monsters).
    • Notes: This one requires a 2000+ attack tribute (maxing out at 3000), to actually get the desired effect, but always forces the selective loss of monsters from the opponent's hand or deck for every 500 atk of the tributed monster. Thankfully it does prevent the use of the destroyed cards for the turn of their loss, which will actually hurt deck like burning abyss where the effects are on the transfer to the grave and not selectively triggered after-the-fact (but many of those cards already had restrictions on using their grave effects the same turn), but it allows for easy grave-loading. Currently this runs 0 in the main deck as it seemed to be accomplishing little, plus it does nothing for the field situation or the hand.
  • Crush Card Virus
    • Symptoms: Wide-spread controllable outbreaks (kills anything over 1500 attack, but with a lot of penalizes attached)
    • Notes: This one got errated hard. It has the deck destruction effect like GGV, but it is optional and basically any deck can find something over 1500 atk that it would like to be in the graveyard. The main thing it does do is wreck the heck out of field, but your opponent is under total LP damage protection for the next 2 turns, so you flat out can not win the game until they have had a chance to respond. Basically the only reason to run this at this point is for The Fang of Critias into Doom Virus Dragon play, but there is no good way to get the Fang in a timely manner.

deck_excerpt: Zombies, counters, and comboes galore! This deck will put a smile on your face and infuriate your friends. It certainly makes mine angry...
deck_description: This is mostly a zombie deck, and is built as such. However, the three trump cards in this deck are Pyramid Turtle, Despair from the Dark, and White-Horned Dragon. White-Horned Dragon is obviously the stand-out of this group, as he is not a zombie card. If you can get Pyramid Turtle early in the duel, lay him face-down in defense mode. Wait for the enemy to destroy him, then activate his card effect and special summon Ryu Kokki. Ryu Kokki's attack is 2400, which is devastating most of the time, and destructive in early game. Alternatively, If you have Zombie monsters on the field whose levels add up to 3 or 7, you could instead use Pyramid Turtle to summon Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries, which is a Tuner monster. You can then utilize Ghost Reaper and any other Zombies you have to Synchro Summon one of the Shuranui cards. Another great monster is Despair from the Dark. As an 8 star, he'll probably stay in your hand for a while. If your opponent activates a card that would destroy him, he'll get sent to the field instead. With his 2800 attack, this is a deadly surprise. White-Horned Dragon is a great monster for late-game. His effect gives the ability to raise his attack up to 3700 (which is difficult to rival). Mix this with Malevolent Nuzzler and Mountain, and he has an utterly destructive 4600. And all for one monster sacrifice. If, at any point, you're dissatisfied with your hand, or you feel your opponent's planning something, simply activate Disturbance Strategy. This will refresh both of your hands. A few more cards I definitely want to note: Spirit Reaper cannot be destroyed in battle. It's incredibly useful in that regard for tributing, especially for White-Horned Dragon. Mix Spirit Reaper with Patrician of Darkness, and you can make it so that none of your opponent's attacks do anything to you. Soul-Absorbing Bone Tower can also be comboed with Spirit Reaper, as attacks can't kill Spirit Reaper, and as long as Spirit Reaper remains alive, attacks can't target Soul-Absorbing Bone Tower. This is a combo useful for preparing to summon Despair from the Dark. WightPrincess is a great card for weakening your enemy. Since it only affects monsters currently on the field, you can discard her, then summon, then destroy the enemy's monster. Alternatively, you could use White-Horned Dragon's low level to your advantage. Since most monsters that can combat him are 8 star, they'd have to have more than a 600-point attack lead to defeat him. Save Trap Hole and Raigeki Break if you get them early. Wait until your opponent thinks they have their trump card, then destroy it. After that, use Monster Reborn to claim their trump card as your own.   There are many more strategies with this deck, and I'll admit it's not perfect (I threw it together with cards I own), but I enjoy it. Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Overwhelm your opponent through swarming, stunning, negating and banishing your way to OTK.
deck_description:
Rank 8 plays with a side of Rank 4's, please. Strategy itself is a classic. Mill your powerhouse level 8 dragons using your wide variety of methods and abuse your ease of access to the graveyard by quickly reviving them. Use Tachyon Transmigration, Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy and Cyber Dragon Infinity to negate attempts to stop your engine, and OTK your opponent as quickly as possible. Card Tips & Combos:
  • Heliosphere Dragon is a minor strategy in of itself. Not only is it a target for Galaxy Soldier, it's also a stall card to sit on while you're waiting for combo pieces. Once you've found one, you can Rank 4 into Galaxy Stealth Dragon using another Heliosphere Dragon or Dragon Knight of Creation, and start pumping out even more dragons from your hand. Alternatively, it can also make itself a level 8 when another level 8 dragon is on the field, which opens up your Rank 8 plays. Dragon Shield can make Heliosphere indestructible even if your opponent surpasses five cards in their hand.
  • Dragon Knight of Creation is fairly versatile, by giving field presence, milling dragons upon destroying a monster, and reviving any dragon by sending itself and a card from your hand to the graveyard. It can be swapped out for Denko Sekka or Ghost Orge & Snow Rabbit (also both Galaxy Soldier targets) if you're facing back-row or effect-heavy decks.
  • Dragunity Arma Leyvaten revives Arkbrave Dragon by attaching him as an equip spell from the grave. Once you overlay Leyvaten for a Rank 8 play, Arkbrave is recycled into the grave again to revive another dragon next turn. It can be swapped out for Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon for even more swarm plays, or Amorphage Goliath if you're fighting other Extra Deck reliant builds.
  • Draconnection can be a good little combo with Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon or Galaxy Stealth Dragon, by letting you pick and choose which level 8 dragon you want to SS from your hand, by trading for something else from your deck. If you have Dragon Ravine or Galaxy Soldier in your hand as well, it can be used in a pinch if you really need to get a Lord Felgrand or Amorphage Goliath into the graveyard, but not the Photon Dragon or Arma Leyvaten sitting in your hand.
  • Rank-Up-Magic - The Seventh One is an instant Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon, which goes into Number C107: Neo Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon, if you draw it for a draw phase. If not? No big deal, just ditch it as cost for Dragon Ravine.
  • People underestimate Galaxy Queen's Light. Instant Rank 8 play with one dragon and any other monster(s) is extremely helpful in a pinch.
  • Quickdraw Synchron synchros with Galaxy Soldier to go into Ultimaya Tzolkein, which SS's powerhouses like Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon and Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons just by setting a spell card before using it. Links nerfed this Extra Deck spam strategy a bit, but it's side decked in case you're not playing link format, or can find a way to make it work in link format.
Note about Link Format: This isn't formatted for links but it can be with minimal edits. Because half our Extra Deck XYZ summons into one another (ergo only requiring our one Extra Monster Zone), if you strategize what you're going to need and use, you won't even need a Link Monster to spam more than one Xyz monster at a time in every duel. Infinity or Titanic Galaxy for negation, Full Armor for popping then goes into Dark Matter for milling, Galaxy Stealth Dragon or Queen Dragon Djinn for swarming and protection, the Cipher Dragons for more shenanigans, and Number 23: Lancelot, Dark Knight of the Underworld or Starliege Paladynamo for additional effects.

deck_excerpt: A degenerate OTK involving the Brandish Spell Engine, Magical Citadel of Endymion and Tempest Magician
deck_description:
The goal: Tempest Magician with 16 tokens (for 8k burn)
  • Keep in mind that Kagari, Hyate and Shizuku will allow you (depending on your level of technical play, as a high level of skill is required to actually survive long enough to pull of the OTK) to beat down on your opponent.
  Main Combos:
  • Toon Table --> 2 other Toon Tables
    • You can pop 1 with Multi-Role, discard for The Tricky or discard to revive Jet if need be
  • Foolish Burial Goods --> Cursed Bamboo --> (if you need a bamboo equip; add broken) add golden bamboo
  • Foolish Burial --> any tuner (setup for Tempest)
  • Magical Citadel + Brandish Spells = counters
    • Brandish Start-Up Engage should be activated after 3 spells in GY to maximize the effectiveness and this is the card you want to abuse/see most often
      • Technical play with Engage + Multi-Role: Use Multi-Role to pop a spell (hopefully something not useful) + Use engage (after 3 in GY, or less than 3 - doesn't matter) --> add Hornet Bit --> SS Kagari --> Add Engage --> use Engage --> SS Hyate --> Battle Phase --> dump Rei (so you can use her, if she isn't in the GY already) --> SS Shizuku --> End Phase --> Activate Multi-Role (add Engage back to field) --> Use Shizuku to add Engage.
        • Assuming you used this combo with 3 spells in GY already, you've got +2 Draw +2 Add --> and that whole set-up for the next turn
You can Summon Tempest off of The Tricky + Needlefiber with a tuner or Tricky + any Tuner
  • In the event that you are able to needlefiber --> SS a Tuner off needlefiber; you should make Linkuriboh with whatever you are able to revive (assuming you have cards in hand for jet and a card in deck for Glow-Up) if need be, you don't have to. Go into Tempest with the Tuner + Tricky --> activate to burn with counters from Magical Citadel + Tempest Magician for 8k (if it's not 8k you can go into Crystal Wing --> needlefiber on your opponent's turn goes into formula synchron which nets a +1 Draw and then a Crystal Wing with your Tempest Magician; you can use this combo at any time, but it's not recommended as it removes the OTK win condition of this deck).

deck_excerpt: The deck’s strength comes from exploiting the effect of Gladiator Beast Secutor in tandem with all the other (old and new) Gladiator Beast cards. Che
deck_description: The main strategy for this deck is to summon Secutor to the field (either by the effect of Test Tiger or any other GB monster), and then start swarming the field with his effect at the end of each battle phase. Ideally, you want Secutor remaining on the field indefinitely but even if you’re only able to resolve his effect once: It can put you so far ahead of your opponent that it’s essentially a win-condition by itself. Another important part of this deck is the Respite engine: Comprising of the card itself, Gladiator Proving Ground and every other card in the deck that has “Gladiator Beast” in its name. They synergize together to make the deck flow easily and consistently, by allowing you to filter through your deck to get to your key cards faster; while also greatly reducing your chances of bricking by allowing you to “reload” your hand if necessary. As with all the other GB cards, Respite can be looped back to your hand via the effect of Equeste, allowing you to re-use Respite multiple times in a single duel. Secutor’s effect can snowball in numerous way: Whether it’s by going +4 through summoning 2x Equeste and resolving both of their effects; or by using the monsters summoned by him to make the Fusion monster Gyzarus, or the Link monster Dragacius. I hope you find the video below helpful in understanding the sort of combos you can do with him, along with the rest of the deck: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ANOY_eC6UGQ Thank you for reading!

deck_excerpt: Odd-Eyes: The deck that does what Magicians do, but with prettier colours. Teach your opponents the value of smiles while beating them to death with a
deck_description: This deck aims to summon Electrumite pre-Pendulum and gain advantage with Arc Pendulum and the aforementioned Electrumite. Incorporates a small Magician engine to take advantage of the 3x Duelist Alliance. Remember to summon Dissolver to fusion summon Vortex Dragon, as this makes him able to be re-summoned later. If not, Absolute Dragon being linked away offers a backdoor way to access him.  If you don't own/don't wish to run Electrumite, here's what I recommend to replace her:  Cut the Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm, the Supreme King Gate Zero, the Dragon Shrines and the Foolish Burials, along with the two Electrumite in the ED. Replace those main deck cards with 2x Pendulum Dragon, 1x Lancer Dragon, 1x Xiangke Magician, 1x Odd-Eyes Fusion, 1x Persona Dragon and 1x Mirage Dragon. The two Electrumites can be replaced with an Odd-Eyes Raging Dragon or Odd-Eyes Rebellion Dragon (food for OE Fusion) and another link such as Underclock Taker or Space Insulator.  Shoutouts to TeamSalmonYGO.

deck_excerpt: Join the Cipher Lords & Grab this deck & give it a spin! I update it every day or every week!
deck_description:
We are the Neo Galaxy-Eyes!

I am here to teach you how to use this intergalactic army or as humans call them a "Deck" this army is a Work in progress so I will be updating this "Deck" a lot so make sure to check back to me every week!

Here is a list of some combinations of "Cards" I've been testing out BUT! These are not complete! New "Cards" are being made as we speak!
Code words: NS [ Normal Summon ] SS [ Special Summon ] XS [ XYZ Summon ] Eff [ Activate a Card Effect ] Add [ Add a card to your hand ]

First Turn:

Just play the deck because first turn isn't the best for setup for this deck!

Second Turn:

Early-Game Combo:

Have in your hand: Galaxy Soldier & Any LIGHT monster [ That you don't need in this combo ] & Photon Vanisher & Galaxy Expedition
Eff Galaxy Soldier SS It, Eff Galaxy Soldier [ When it's SS'ed you can add a "Galaxy" Monster to your hand ] Add Galaxy-Eyes Cloudragon then, use Galaxy Expedition and SS Galaxy Knight then, SS Photon Vanisher using his Effect and Add Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon then, NS Galaxy-Eyes Cloudragon use it's effect to SS your Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from your hand then, you have a couple options!

Option 1:

If your opponent got a good hand and is completely set up XS either Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord or Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy [ Photon Lord for Monsters & being unable to be destroyed my card effects. And Titanic Galaxy for Spells, Traps & Monsters ]

Option 2:

If your opponent got a bad/neutral hand and is barely set up or have any hand traps XS either Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon then XS into Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon or [ If the situation calls for it & you have it in your hand you can XS! the almighty, Neo Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon! using Rank-Up-Magic: Cipher Ascension! ] or Number 62: Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon or Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon

Late-Game Combo:

This combo is very good for stalling when you need cards but you need a really specific field...

First, you need: a Field with Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord, then you need to be losing with less LP than your opponent & have a lot of "Galaxy" monsters in your graveyard.

Use the Effect of Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord [ He can add a "Photon or "Galaxy" to him as material or to your hand. When it says: "Add this card to your hand?" after you choose a card say "Yes" to add it to your hand and "No" to add it as material ] Add Galaxy Mirror Sage to your hand then set him face down. When it's your opponents turn make sure they attack the face down, when they do u will be able to use the Effect of Galaxy Mirror Sage and you gain loads of LP and when it's destroyed & sent to the grave [ After being flipped face up ] you can SS a LVL 4 or under "Galaxy" monster from the grave. Now if you have a Galaxy Mirror Sage in your grave you can SS it FACE DOWN! so you can keep doing this combo forever! [ Though if you don't have another Galaxy Mirror Sage in your grave just do the same combo next turn ]

The End for now...

And thats all that I have thought of but I will be updating this all the time! and I hope you check this out, Leave a like, and try to get to popular decks this week!

We got to POPULAR DECKS THIS WEEK!

The main strategy of this deck is to get an OTK with Frighfur Sabre-Tooth and Kraken. Here's the OTK: (You want to go second)
  1. Use things like Patchwork, King of the Swamp, and Bear to get 2 Polymerization into your hand.
  2. Fusion Summon Kraken.
  3. Use Kraken's effect to destroy a monster on your opponent's field (if they summoned last turn)
  4. Use the 2nd Polymerization to Fusion Summon Sabre-Tooth
  5. Use Sabre-Tooth's effect, which will bring Kraken back into the field.
  6. Enter the Battle Phase.
  7. Because of Sabre-Tooth's effect, his attack will be 2800, and Kraken's will be 2600
  8. Since your opponent has no monsters (preferably), attack directly
  9. Attack with Sabre-Tooth, 8000 - 2800 = 5200
  10. Attack with Kraken, 5200 - 2600 = 2600
  11. Kraken's effect allows him to attack twice. 2600 - 2600 = 0
  12. GG!

deck_excerpt: very good blue eyes deck (it blows these other blue eyes decks out of the water, pretty much making them worthless)
deck_description: blue eyes are one of the most versatile decks in yugioh, so far. this deck is even better than the others though. it's a guaranteed good first hand as long as you know what you're doing with it. because the first hand is always random there is really no way to make a good strategy guide for this deck. all i can do for you is tell you how to get out either true king or crystal wing (they have the same requirements) with what you have. what's best is if you use a glow-up bulb and synchro it with any level 8 monster into blue-eyes spirit dragon, use glow-up's effect to bring it back onto the field, now you have to choose whether you want true king or crystal wing.  if you chose true king: use spirit's effect to bring out stardust spark, synchro that and glow-up (or another lvl 1 tuner) into cloudcastle, use cloudcastle's effect to special summon spirit from the graveyard, xyz summon true king.  if you chose crystal wing: use spirit's effect to bring out moonlight, synchro moonlight and glow-up (or another lvl 1 tuner) into crystal wing.  other than that you'll just have to adjust your strategy for what the battle calls for.  plus it's good in both link and mr3 (both strategies work exactly the same in link and in mr3)  hope this helped  ps. i would love to hear your opinions on how to make this deck better

The biggest issues I've run into while trying to use Coelecanth are the reliance on normal summons and a lack of good search tools.  Brilliant Fusion into Seraphinite and Baobaboon with Dragonic Diagram are there to remedy these problems while also providing a possible win condition with Metaltron XII.  If this deck works properly, it can deal well over 8000 points of damage in one turn.  The current list is a bit bricky atm but I will continue to tweak it.  I will also add a side deck once I am happy with the main deck.  I know this deck looks messy, but I swear there was a reason for each card at some point.  If people would like a more detailed explanation of the strategy and card choices, just let me know.  I am also open to suggestions for card changes, make sure to indicate which card(s) would be removed for any new additions.

After way more testing with Altergeists this is the build I came up with. It performed extremely well in testing and I was able to go 6-0 on Ygopro using this deck. I had to edit the ratios so much over the course of the past two weeks and this is the final product! Also my last Altergeist build messed up and the file can't be downloaded for whatever reason so sorry about that. The goal of this deck is to go first and set traps and then use them next turn to trigger Altergeist Multifaker and blow up the field with Altergeists and interruptions. I added Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries to the main deck because it stops the current meta decks completely by having meta Cherry targets in the extra deck like Heavymetalfoes Electrumite for pendulums, Spyral Double Helix for Spyrals, etc... Also there is Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon in the extra deck. That is a Cherries target for Raidraptors, but it's mainly for the side deck card Waking The Dragon. During game two, if your opponent sides properly they will want to destroy your backrow since Altergeists rely on backrow. You can set Waking The Dragon and when they destroy it, you can summon Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon and then you win the game because Ultimate Falcon is almost impossible to deal with since it can only be Kaijud or destroyed by battle. One really cool combo going first to help you if you're new to Altergeists is if you draw Altergeist Meluseek going first and you didn't draw Multifaker, you can normal summon Meluseek and then link into Linkuriboh and use Meluseek's effect to add Multifaker to your hand! Enjoy the deck.

deck_excerpt: Wipe your opponents entire board with ease with the fires of Armageddon in this Unorthodox deck.
deck_description: Armageddon is a OTK deck with two possible methods of OTKing your opponent. I'll try to make this as brief as possible. Dozered: The first possible OTK is This hand. Manju, Ritual/or/Demise, and Megamorph and Doom Dozer. if the opponent is not running Monster Effect counters you can wipe the board with Demise's effect Taking 2000LP and more than likely leaving you with less health then your opponent. When you ritual summon if you have Doom Dozer in hand send both Neo Bug and Insect Knight to the graveyard. this allows you to SS Doom Dozer. Once you've finished this apply Megamorph to Doom Dozer and BOOM you got an OTK. Blue Eyes: The second method is to Have Manju, Ritual/or/Demise, Megamorph, and Swing of Memories the same pattern applies as above however instead of sacrificing Insects you sacrifice Blue-Eyes White Dragon. Once you've cleared the board use Swing of Memories and bring Blue eyes back. then apply Megamorph and once again you've got an OTK. I've played around 50 games with this deck and it has run though its Great games and its bad games. If any players have any suggestions please leave a comment and i will overview it. Thanks a lot Blason!

deck_excerpt: This Special Atlantean Mermail deck had proven to be one of the stable ones. Use the Toad, Kaiju, F.A. Dawn, and Tri-gate Wizard to negate ur opponent
deck_description:
Please read the deck description below as certain combos are quite complicated. Advices for the Deck The deck is not fixed. If you want to have a lower chance of brick, you could well take away one Atlantean Marksman and one Atlantean Heavy Infantry and add in Surface or Aqua Spirit. These cards also help control the graveyard to summon Moulinglacia. The same goes for adding a few cards to prevent ur opponent from disrupting ur combo. Take away Infantry and Marksman (if you think 3 terraforming is too bricky, take away one) and add in Called by the Grave or Twin Twisters or Cosmic Cyclone. Two Abyss-Scales equip spell cards are also applicable, as it adds extra protection and makes OTK real easy if you equip it to Mermail Abyssmegalo. Adding one copy of Dupe Frog seems to also work as Toadally Awesome would be able to summon a fixed Attack target next Standby Phase, and the Dupe Frog would be able to search for the last Swap Frog if it was sent from the field to the graveyard, and potentially bring back Toadally Awesome again. But I personally find the card bricky in certain cases and didn't add it. Remember you can edit the deck according to ur play style. Combo 1 Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince + Mermail Abyssteus
  1. Summon the prince, use effect to throw Atlantean Dragoons into the grave.
  2. Dragoon search for a Mermail Abyssmegalo and Prince search for another Atlantean Dragoons
  3. Summon Mermail Abyssteus by throwing away Atlantean Dragoons into the grave
  4. Atlantean Dragoons search for Moulinglacia the Elemental Lord, Mermail Abyssteus search for Mermail Abyssgunde
  5. Summon Riplodocus using Prince and Abyssteus
  6. Summon Abyssmegalo by throwing Abyssgunde and a random water monster into the grave (leave the spot below Riplodocus open)
  7. Abyssgunde effect revives Abyssteus
  8. You have 5 water monsters in the grave, so summon Moulinglacia below Riplodocus
  9. Use Riplodocus effect to change Moulinglacia type to dinosaur
  10. Summon Summon Sorceress using Riplodocus and Moulinglacia
  11. Summon Number 42: Galaxy Tomahawk under Summon Sorceress
  12. Use Tomahawk effect to summon 4 token
  13. Use 2 token to make Proxy Dragon
  14. Use Tomahawk and 1 token to make Knightmare Goblin beside the Proxy Dragon
  15. Activate Goblin effect throw away one card and draw one, and then normal summon a random monster next to Goblin
  16. Use Goblin and the random monster to summon a Trigate Wizard
  17. Use Summon Sorceress effect to summon Knightmare Corruptor Iblee (because it's pointing to Proxy Dragon)
  18. Use Iblee and Summon Sorceress to summon Knightmare Gryphon
  19. Iblee will be summoned on ur opponent's field
  20. If you prefer, use Gryphon to bring back any spell cards from the grave
  21. Remember the last token? Use that to summon Link Spider above the Trigate Wizard
  22. You must also realise that this combo work best when it's a 3 card combo, to make Proxy Dragon work you must have another monster next to it. So for example if you had a swap frog in ur hand, you could normal summon it using Goblin, it throws Ronintoadin into the grave, link it away, and it gives you an extra Ronintoadin available to summon next to the Proxy Dragon.
  Combo 2 Terraforming (or Kyoutou Waterfront) + Destrudo the Lost Dragon's Frisson + any monster you can normal summon with (not Deep Sea Diva or Ronintoadin)
  1. Activate Terraforming to search for Kyoutou Waterfront and activate that.
  2. Normal summon the monster
  3. summon Destrudo by activating its effect
  4. Summon Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing
  5. Use Yazi effect to pop one opponent card
  6. summon Mare Mare
  7. Mare Mare effect to summon 3 token
  8. Summon Linkuriboh and Link Spider
  9. Use the 4 monsters to summon Saryuja Skull Dread
  10. Skull Dread draws
  11. Use Waterfront to search for Kaiju
  12. Skull Dread special summons the Kaiju
  13. You will find most times in this combo that you will be able to summon other monsters due to Skull Dread's drawing effect. Such as an extra Toadally Awesome if you managed to draw Swap Frog. Dawn Dragster is also possible to summon next turn as Destrudo is in the graveyard.
Combo 3 Swap Frog + any water monster
  1. use frog effect to rid of the water monster, summon the frog and throw Ronintoadin into the graveyard.
  2. Bounce frog back and normal summon it again
  3. frog effect throw another swap frog into the grave
  4. use Ronintoadin effect get it back on the field
  5. Summon Toadally Awesome
Combo 4 (OTK combo) Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince + (Optional) Mermail Abyssteus or Mermail Abyssmegalo The one card combo works when you have Prince and 3 other water monsters in hand. If you have another Abyssteus or Abyssmegalo in hand, it would be a lot easier to carry out the combo.
  1. summon Prince, use effect to throw Atlantean Dragoons into the grave
  2. Prince search for another Dragoons, Dragoons search for Abyssmegalo
  3. Summon Abyssmegalo by throwing Dragoons and another random water monster from hand
  4. Dragoon search for another Abyssmegalo
  5. Summon Abyssmegalo by throwing away 2 random water monsters
  6. Use Abyssmegalo effect to attack twice by tributing Prince
  7. Prince effect activates and revives Atlantean Dragoons
  8. now you have 9000 worth of damage, enough to OTK ur opponent
  9. This combo improves a lot if you have Abyss-Scale equip spell cards in the deck. I didn't include it in this deck as this deck is mainly focused on bringing monsters that can negate ur opponent. But if you want to OTK, consider adding Abyss-Scale cards into the deck (usually one  Cetus,  one Mizuchi)

deck_excerpt: Pure Abyss Actor OTK Deck 2018 (Post Mellow Madonna)
deck_description: Upon special requests to make this deck, I have been testing Abyss Actors from scratch and this deck is very casual but can go up against tier two decks without losing. I normally do not upload OCG based decks or decks with OCG cards in them since I live in the USA and want to stick to the current meta game we have in the TCG. I have found this Pure Abyss Actor deck to be fun to play and there are many combos hidden within the deck to be discovered for people who are trying this specific deck for the first time. The combos involve the Abyss Actor cards themselves and the extra deck monsters, especially Heavymetalfoes Electrumite. This deck utilizes all of the Abyss Actor monsters and the Abyss Actor spell cards with no other pendulum monsters in the deck since it is Pure Abyss Actors. Making a build that relies on summoning Heavymetalfoes Electrumite going first and setting up interruptions could be a good meta deck once the new Abyss Actor cards come out in the TCG. I have found this deck to be most effective going second because you can actually OTK your opponent on that second turn! One cool combo I love in this deck is when you're going second and your opponent has a monster and you have none while you have Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser or Abyss Actor - Extras in your hand. You can summon one, or both of those monsters and then normal summon if you only special summoned one of the two to make Electrumite and send Abyss Actor - Wild Hope off Electrumite's effect. Then, you activate a scale and pop it using Electrumite's effect to add Wild Hope back to your hand and draw one. Next, activate Wild Hope in scale and any other Abyss Actor monster for the other scale and use Wild Hope's effect to make the other scale a nine scale. Lastly, pendulum summon four or five monsters and OTK! I love this combo because your opponent just gets OTKd out of nowhere and it's very funny. Hope you enjoy the deck and have fun figuring out all the other fun combos!
x
Watch how to use this deck in YGO Lite (Youtube).  Link : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jY8pJXRm69U&feature=youtu.be

After months of testing via trial and error, I found (and hopefully wasn't the only one) a way to make Mekk-knight summons even better. When the Dark Saviors set came out this year, it introduced Vampires, Brandish (Sky Striker Aces), and Skyfang Brigade (Fur Hire). To make things simpler I decided to test out the Mekk-Knight build with the Brandish engine and found out that its actually really consistent in terms of summons. As long as the main field is empty you can spam the brandish spells to get your monsters on the field to special summon the Mekk-knight of your choice and continue the chain. Only problem is whether or not you can get the cards to get that said chain started. If you think this deck is still inconsistent feel free to alter the card list to suit your play-style...  I will give a bit of advice; once you get the sky striker of your choice on field, try to get the link-2 Mekk-Knight Morning Star on field to have a bit of advantage. Outside of that, I hope you enjoy...

Going to YouTube videos is a great way to learn the combos to this deck for those who are new to Spyral Knightmares. Just type Spyral Knightmare combos on YouTube and you will find a good video that will help you. Or, if you know Spyrals really well then you should have no problem playing the deck. The Knightmare link spam has truly made Spyrals over powered. Enjoy the deck and have fun!

Hope you guys enjoy this Deck. Super Quantum cards have Unique abilities to Summon / Shuffle from grave / or add to hand This combos well with their XYZ counter parts the Super Quantal Beasts. Super Quantal Beasts are able to use their effects for effective board control not only that but the stat lining is no joke either. In order of my favorites:

Super Quantal Mech Beast Magnaliger: I thoroughly enjoy this card not only for his effect of destroying any monster on the board but his stat lining combined with Magnaslayer can cause an OTK

Super Quantal Mech Beast Grampulse: Second we have Grampulse with his ability for removing any Spell/Trap on the field with a rather sturdy defense it won't be going anywhere soon in combat.

Super Quantal Mech Beast Aeroboros: Aerboros is my least favorite due to a Moderate stat lining and a sub par Effect Change a monster to face down Defense.

Once you have used all three Super Quantal Mech Beasts  you'll be able to summon you're boss monster Super Quantal Mech King Great Magnus: if you're able to get this monster onto the field you're guaranteed the win. Any recommendations or change please leave a comment! -Sorry for the brief Analysis got a party to attend to!

deck_excerpt: This deck started out as a joke deck with roughly 37 dog-themed monster cards and 3 Where Arf Thou?'s. Since then, it's evolved to be a legitimately p
deck_description: This deck started out as a joke deck with roughly 37 dog-themed monster cards and 3 Where Arf Thou?'s. Since then, it's evolved to be a legitimately playable deck outside of the current meta. Now, the deck is built around using Flamvell Firedog's effect to special summon other fire monsters with under 200 DEF, these mainly being the 6* Hazy Flame Cerberus and the 4* Diceclops. XYZ summoning with Diceclops and Firedog allows you access to huge staples, such as Number 39: Utopia and Gagagigo the Risen. Using Firedog's effect to summon Cerberus ends up with an XYZ summon of Gauntlet Launcher instead. (there aren't a lot of dog XYZs.) Where Arf Thou? is still in the deck, mainly used to summon Slacker Magician in one turn using Outstanding Dog Marron as material. This can be done easily with Double Summon.

A crazy combo deck which consistently leads to a board with Saryuja Skull Dread, Lord Of The Red, ABC - Dragon Buster, Invoked Mechaba, Ancient Gear Megaton Golem and Chimeratech Rampage Dragon. The deck works by giving Ryu Okami to your opponent through Summon Sorceress and milling Cyber Dragon Nova to special summon machine fusion monsters from the extra deck. The deck won't work if the opponent's zones in front of the extra monster zones are occupied or if either Summon Sorceress or Ryu Okami get negated. Having Ryu Okami in your hand is mandatory for the deck to work: destroy Mariamne with Diagram or another Mariamne to search it out. Second step is to summon Summon Sorceress, which you can do in three ways
  • discard Rosenix or Thystvern to special summon Sulfefnir, destroy it with its effect to summon Citree and use Rosenix's token or Thystvern's search to go into Needlefiber, use its effect to special summon another Citree and go into Sorceress;
  • special summon Terrortop and bring out Taketomborg, then summon any Crystron and go directly into Sorceress;
  • summon a True King and Al-Lumi'raj to go Needlefiber -> Citree -> Sorceress; Al-Lumi'raj can be brought out by destroying Bahrastos.
Now the combo begins: special summon Ryu Okami to your opponent's field with Sorceress' first effect, then use its second effect to bring out a True King: this way Ryu will start milling your Extra Deck. Megaton is a big beater, Mechaba negates, ABC banishes, Chimeratech dumps ABC's materials and attacks multiple times, Omega recycles Nova and Herald, Herald searches Lord Of The Red and Advanced Ritual Art, Nova summons fusions (except ABC) and Saryuja and Goblin expand your Extra Monster Zones.

deck_excerpt: If your looking for troll and casualties this is the deck for you "LETS CRANK IT UP" with this deck.
deck_description: Very casual deck surrounding the archetype Wind-ups. Wind-up cards are dependant on special summoning and their effect in which can support one another such as a Burning Abyss deck. This deck is easy to xyz and link summon giving you loads of opportunities to get the upper hand.

Finally I have finished this deck. First of all, this deck is so much fun to play in my opinion so please enjoy the deck! I have play tested this deck so much from scratch and it has become really good. I was able to beat Trickstar Sky Striker three times in a row with this deck and many other meta and tier two decks. The goal of the deck is to always go second and special summon Kaijus to your opponents field in the same column as their spell/traps are and then special summon Mekk-Knights! Psi-Blocker is super helpful too to block off cards your opponent needs to win once you know what deck they are playing. Use Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries to dominate meta players and make them banish their core pieces. Waking The Dragon is really good to side in against decks that like removing your backrow. Once they try to remove it they will be stuck with Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon on your side of the field and that will win you the game! Spell Absorption is a spicy tech card I threw in to help counter Trickstars and Chain Burn since they inflict so much damage. One awesome combo I love to do is special summon Mekk-Knight Blue Sky and then normal summon Cherries or Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and synchro into PSY-Framelord Omega. Hope you enjoy!

After making many Burning Abyss builds from scratch trying to create spicy techs this is the one I have made as the final product. It never bricks and can go first or second. Going second is better though since this build runs a lot of handtraps for many reasons. The ghost girls are used to stop your opponent from doing pretty much everything, not only are they good handtraps but you can use them as synchro material with the other Burning Abyss monsters so they aren't bricks in your hand your upcoming turn! That is why this build plays three Libic, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss so that you can send Libic to the graveyard and use his effect to special summon a Burning Abyss monster from your hand and negate its effects. This way you can normal summon a ghost girl and go into Brionac, Dragon of the Ice Barrier or Gravity Warrior which is another cool tech I added in. Gravity Warrior is good to use when you're opponent has a lot of monsters on their board and you don't have access to Black Luster Soldier. Since Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit and Effect Veiler are light monsters, they can be used as material for Black Luster Soldier. Also, Virgil isn't dead! Synchro into Virgil, Rock Star of the Burning Abyss in this build using Rubic, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss and the other Burning Abyss monsters. Virgil's shuffle effect is very powerful even in today's meta. After testing I have won games because of Virgil! Enjoy the deck and have fun guys.

deck_excerpt: A simple Fluffal deck that's very cheap but also pretty effective.
deck_description: Main Deck: 3x Edge Imp Tomahawk: Can turn itself into any “edge imp” card. Summon with Sheep instead of normal summoning if possible. Price: $0.14  3x Edge Imp Chain: Searches a fusion card or counter trap when sent to the graveyard. Also necessary for a very good fusion monster. Price: $0.05  3x Edge Imp Sabres: Necessary for almost all the fusions we do, and it can revive itself too boot. Price: $0.15  3x Fluffal Owl: Searches Polymerization, and can fuse by itself if needed. Price: $0.10  3x Fluffal Sheep: Allows us to use Edge Imp monster’s effects more often. Very good for late-game. Price: $0.09  3x Fluffal Cat: Recycles our Polymerizations. Price: $0.05  3x Fluffal Rabbit: Recycles our Fluffal and Edge Imp monsters. Price: $0.07  3x Frightfur Fusion: Late-game fusion that allows for massive otk’s and board wipes with Frightfur Wolf and Tiger. Price: $0.12  3x Polymerization: Unfortunately, this card is necessary in order for us to summon anything. Don’t waste any. Price: $0.57  1x Dark Hole: Wipes both player’s boards. Good for when you’re behind drastically. Price: $0.08  3x Suture Rebirth: Allows us to recover beaters after a couple turns. If used on Frightfur Sheep, the resurrection effect still works! Price: $0.09  2x Night Beam: Spell and Trap destruction, used in any decent deck-build. Price: $0.16  2x Fluffal Crane: Deck thinning, allowing us to recover from our opponent destroying our on-board fusion material. Price: $0.06  2x Mirror Force: One of the best monster removal cards at this price range. Price: $0.20  3x Frightfur March: Helps our Frightfur monsters stay alive longer. Price: $0.10  Extra Deck:  1x Frightfur Chimera: Our target for Frightfur March. Has a very big body and can give decent rewards since the card you resummon doesn’t have its effects negated. Price: $0.05  2x Frightfur Wolf: OTK machine. 4 Materials = 8000 damage to face. Also very nice for OTK through low ATK boards. Price: $0.08  2x Frightfur Tiger: Most of the time, this will nuke all the cards your opponent can use. Just think carefully about what you choose. Price: $0.20  2x Frightfur Sheep: Very durable monster that can be buffed to insane levels. Keep in mind that  when resurrected it will move out of the extra monster zone and into the main monster zone. Price: $0.10   2x Space Insulator: Great vertical arrows that can be made with anything. Make this card first before other Link monsters. Price: $0.01

deck_excerpt: A budget metalfoes deck good for those who want a good quality starter deck.
deck_description:
Main Deck:

The next few cards are metalfoes’ normal monster lineup. Their pendulum effects are all the same, so the only details I’ll leave is where their preferred location is.

3x Metalfoes Volflame: In Extra deck Price: $0.11

 

3x Metalfoes Goldriver: In Extra deck Price: $0.24

 

3x Metalfoes Silverd: On Pendulum Zone Price: $0.10

3x Metalfoes Steelen: On Pendulum Zone Price: $0.03

 

3x Rescue Rabbit: Best card in the deck, hands-down. Allows a free link monster and if you have a 1 and 8-scale pendulum monster in hand, a fusion monster. Just make sure to play other cards so that you can bait out any negations the opponent might have. Price: $0.50

 

3x Archfiend Eccentrick: Spell, Trap, and Monster removal in one card! Price: $0.12

 

3x Raremetalfoes Bismugear: If it gets destroyed by your opponent or your own card (likely other Metalfoes monsters) Price: $0.05

 

3x Painful Decision: Searches out any Metalfoes monster while filling our graveyard for Mithrillium. Price: $0.13

 

1x Dark Hole: Great board wipe. Price: $0.10

 

3x Metalfoes Fusion: Our main fusion card. Can recycle for draw power if needed. Price: $0.10

 

3x Fullmetalfoes Fusion: Fusion summons on your opponent’s turn! Most of the time, you will be summoning Fullmetalfoes Alkahest with this card. Price: $0.04

 

3x Metalfoes counter: Brings out monsters to replace our dead ones.Price: $0.02

 

3x Dimension Guardian: This card protects our monsters from most threats. Especially useful on link monsters. Price: $0.10

 

3x Metalfoes Combination: With this, we can use a card for fusion material in the hand, then place it back on the field. Or, fusion summon any level 7 or lower fusion monster, then use it to summon Orichalc and bring it right back. Price: $0.06

 

Extra Deck:

 

2x Metalfoes Orichalc: Big body that can damage your opponent through defense monsters. Also high leveled for combination plays. Price: $0.03

2x Metalfoes Mithrilium: Recycles cards and removes monsters all at the same time. Price: $0.10

1x Metalfoes Adamante: (Almost) guaranteed target for fusion with Alkahest’s effect. Price: $0.03

2x Fullmetalfoes Alkahest: Steals opponent’s monsters in the middle of their plays, stopping them in their tracks. You can also summon fusion monsters with the monsters you stole, allowing greater board presence on the next turn. Price: $0.10

1x Zefra Metaltron: Using a Chimera and 2 Metalfoes monsters, you can summon a monster which can remove your opponent’s monsters temporarily and recycle resources when your opponent removes a Metalfoes monster. Price: $0.09

 

2x Do-little Chimera: Our main link monster. Gives our Metalfoes an attack boost and can add either itself or a Metalfoes from the Graveyard into your hand upon death. Price: $0.10

deck_excerpt: Add Exodia Pieces from your Banished Pile by using Pot of Desires & Primal Seed.
deck_description: An Exodia FTK/OTK Build with a ton of potential, built around banishing your Exodia pieces & returning them to your hand with Primal Seed. There is room to include Called by the Grave & other Floodgates without effecting combo's. The Deck is built on 3 Combos; 1. ISOLDE: Opening up with "Armageddon Knight" will let you send "Destiny Hero - Malicious" to the GY, allowing you to Special Summon another copy to Link into Isolde. Search and add "Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning" to your hand OR another "Armageddon Knight" if you have "Allure of Darkness"/ "Hand Destruction" in Hand. Use Isolde to send an Equip spell to the GY to special summon "Destiny Hero - Dark Angel" & if possible Special Summon another copy of Malicious. You can Link into most LINK - 4 monsters from here or into "Decode Talker" & "Linkuriboh". Also if you have a copy of One for One in hand you can Link into Saryuja. 2. SERIAL SPELL: Opening up with "Pot of Desires" & "Serial Spell" is almost always a Win. It should draw enough power to get you BLS & Primal Seed first turn, and banish enough to allow you to continue your plays with Primal Seed. 3. GRINDER GOLEM / ONE DAY OF PEACE: If you open the duel with these 2 Cards in your hand, you're almost GUARANTEED a FTK with Exodia. **The best thing about Armageddon Knight & Isolde, is you can use them to thin your deck out prior to playing big draw power cards.** Enjoy this build. I've beaten top tier decks going second & siding in 3x "Called by the Grave" instead of 1x "Dark World Dealings" | 1x "Armageddon Knight" | 1x "Serial Spell" .

deck_excerpt: A Dinosaur-Deck (Evolution Pill) which uses Volcanics for a 1-time field nuke.
deck_description:
This is a Dinosaur-Deck (Evolution Pill-based) which uses Volcanics for a 1-time field nuke (afterwards as banishing material for Double Evolution Pill). As a "Boss-monster" I use Ultimate Conductor Tyranno (UCT), which is mostly summoned by evo. pill. Evolzars are not as big, but provide protection in form of negation.
The playmakers are Oviraptor/Foolish Burial with Overtex. Banishing Giant Rex (if possible) and Oviraptor on the field provide you with materials for ranked 4 Evolzar. Foolish Burial Goods + Blaze Acc. Reload provide the fieldnuke.
The Deck is certainly not Top-Tier, but can hold its ground quite well against them if you don't brick, which does not happen too often, but drawing 3 scattershots is quite painful. A weakness of this deck is search negation/prohibition, since the deck has very low draw-power, but good searching power (Fossil Dig, Oviraptor + Overtex, Foolish Burial [Goods], and many more). It's for sure a "blast" to play with this deck. ;) Have fun! Juliner

deck_excerpt: 60 Card Burning Abyss Invoked (Super Fun And Meta Relevant)
deck_description: Ok, now I know what you're thinking. That this deck doesn't work well right? Well, guess again! The Invoked Engine with Burning Abyss works super well. This deck also has a very low brick rate. After building this deck from scratch, testing, and making many edits I found the ratios that work. I was able to beat many meta decks and many tier two decks. The decks goal is to go second and win in two turns, or otk on the second turn after your opponent used up all their resources their first turn to setup. Another thing to remember when playing this deck is that you need to make Dante so you can mill cards from your deck to graveyard like Fairy Tail - Snow. Snow is a big pain to deal with, so stack up your graveyard! This deck gives so many resources to you because while you have the Burning Abyss monsters in your hand or Dante on the field, you also have either a boss monster in your hand like Black Luster Soldier, Orbital Hydralander, or Aleister The Invoker which gives you even more boss monsters and resources after your opponent has run out since normally your opponent will only have one or two boss monsters after they've finished their first turn. The deck also mains many handtraps so going second is a breeze and you can make your opponent lose a lot of their resources if you play the handtraps at the correct time. Since the deck runs so many handtraps, plus having your opponents graveyard at your disposal, going into Invoked Mechaba, and Invoked Purgatrio is easy. On the other hand, if you are forced to go first by your opponent, making Invoked Caliga is very effective at stopping your opponent from doing anything monster effect related turn two. Since many of the decks monsters are dark you shouldn't have a hard time making Caliga going first. There are so many cool tech cards I added in to the deck to make it so great! Creature Swap is a great one that I love using on my opponent, and I prefer this over Mind Control because Mind Control can cause your Burning Abyss monsters to blow themselves up while Creature Swap doesn't and still allows you to use their effects after you destroy them via battle or card effect. Another amazing combo I love doing is with Tour Bus From The Underworld. This card is super effective late game because if you mill it and you've used Beatrice already, you can shuffle her back into the extra deck to make her again! I also don't like using Terraforming and Magical Meltdown in this deck because after testing I've realized that since Magical Meltdown counts as a spell card, it prevents you from special summoning the Burning Abyss monsters. Lastly, if you don't like Pot of Desires, which I do in this deck since you play so many three ofs, you can swap it out with three Allure of Darkness instead and the deck will still work well. Enjoy and have fun!

deck_excerpt: Dark Magician and Buster Blade deck
deck_description: Have fun. Now dab.

I know I have already posted a True King Dino deck already, but I felt I should make another one from scratch to see if it can be anymore better and after testing I feel that this one is more updated and better than my old one. I was able to beat a lot of meta decks with this TKD build. The goal of this deck is to go second and otk them that second turn. This deck hardly ever bricks, in fact every time I've played it I've never had a bad hand. The part of the deck that I noticed it struggles with the most is dealing with backrow so to solve that problem I put a lot of backrow removal in the side deck. Red Reboot is so good in this deck since you want to go second and you can just use Red Reboot on your opponent during your first turn (second turn of the game) so they can't use backrow anymore is so good because then you can just otk them freely without worrying about all their backrow that will stop you. Set Rotation is also super effective against decks that run field spells like ABC, Lair of Darkness, Pure Dinosaurs, etc... One of my awesome spicy techs I put into the deck is Ally of Justice Catastor. If your opponent has any monster that's not dark type and is a problem for you at that moment you can use Catastor to destroy it. I also love playing this deck because going second they get otkd out of nowhere on the second turn and then don't really know what happened, it's funny. Please enjoy the deck and if you have any questions don't hesitate to ask!

deck_excerpt: THIS DECK WORKS PRETTY WELL. PLEASE GIVE FEEDBACK
deck_description:
This deck has worked fairly well for me and uses most of the Red-Eyes cards except for I think B. Chick, Darkness (love the artwork, but not worth it IMO), Metal, and vanilla.

I've been tweaking it a bit, so it's still not perfect. I've added Full Force Virus to test out sending Flare Dragon or Meteor Dragon to GY and bringing it back with Return of the Red-Eyes to eliminate low defense monsters with Deck Devastation Virus sided if I need to eliminate low attack instead.

If you want to fusion summon Archfiend Black Skull Dragon with Red-Eyes Fusion, then you're either going to want to run a single Summoned Skull or try to get Red-Eyes Archfiend of Lightning on the field. Alternatively you can just send Archfiend to the GY using Red-Eyes Insight if you have Dragon's Mirror in hand.

I also have a Red-Eyes deck that basically just dumps dragons to revive them and Divine Dragon Lord Felgrand, but it's probably a little more pricey than this one and uses fewer Red-Eyes cards.

After testing with this deck for about a week now I have finally found the right ratios that work well. This deck is extremely overwhelming going second, so going second is your best bet at winning. I have been able to beat almost all the meta decks using this deck so it is very powerful and can win almost every time. It has has a low brick rate. The goal of the deck is simple, to go second and handtrap your opponent when they are going first and then use their graveyard and/or your handtraps in your hand or grave for Invoked fusion material. You also have the Sky Striker cards at your disposal to draw more cards and use Sky Striker Ace - Kagari as fusion material for Invoked Purgatrio. Set Rotation is really great to screw decks that use a field spell and it's also another Terraforming basically because you want spell cards in your grave to use the second effect of the Sky Striker cards. Some games I've even been able to get Decode Talker plus two Invoked Mechabas or an Invoked Mechaba and an Invoked Purgatrio depending on how many Invocations I have in hand. This deck is also really good to bait your opponent into wasting their handtraps on the wrong cards e.g. when you have Aleister The Invoker in your hand plus Sky Stiker Mobilize - Engage! and use Engage to bait their Ash Blossom and then summon Aleister to search Invocation. Enjoy and have fun.

deck_excerpt: Consistent way of summoning Herald and Kristya ending with 4-6 cards in hand.
deck_description: GOING FIRST: 1. with gale dogra: -2 herald of the arc light in GY for 2 searches -2 lvl 6 (either herald or idaten) using benten as the tribute (searching fluffal wings the second time) -> beatrice -> toy vendor in GY -> search fluffal bear -> use fluffal bear's effect -> use toy vendor to discard fluffal wings -> use fluffal wings from GY -summon herald tributing benten -> search archlord kristya -(be sure to have 4 fairies in GY at this point) SP archlord kristya   2. without gale dogra: exactly the same as above except: -when summoning the first lvl 6 search cyber petit angel with benten -normal summon cyber petit angel -summon a link 2 using beatrice and cyber petit angel -be sure to have 4 fairies in GY at this point   3. Side decking going first: -demise, fiend of armageddon against counter traps (it can be sent to the GY via beatrice during the opponent's turn or by tributing it along with the monster you normal sumoned for a ritual summon)     GOING SECOND: 1. without side decking: -the most destructive play is: -summon natasha tributing benten (search petit angel if you don't have gale dogra) -normal summon -summon a link 2 -use natasha from grave -etc. etc. etc. depending on the situation   2. with side decking -self explanatory I guess...     NOTE: -I don't have any handtraps in the main/side deck. I suggest these: -3 called by the grave going first (droll & lock bird, artifact lancea and winter cherries are the only handtraps that can stop you) and from these only droll & ock bird is played so it is the only reason for playing called by the grave -3 infinite transcience going second: it's usefull even if you don't use it that turn (unlike gamma/veiler), it can be used more than OPT (unlike ash blossom/ghost ogre) and is the only handtrap that is unnafected by called by the grave/aqua dolphin -this isn't one of those decks that can win with 2 cards combo (except gale dogra + pre-prep or stuff like that) so it can't run many handtraps anyway. This is its biggest weakness. (more or less the weakness of all ritual decks)     OTHER SUGGESTIONS: -foolish mass burial -insect imitation (search fluffal wings normal summon it and use insect imitation to special summon gale dogra from deck) -devirituals (maybe even emergency teleport/lonefire blossom) -celestial sextant -machine angel absolute ritual (1 card board wiping combo with gale dogra, this card and vrash) -Eva (can be sent to GY with beatrice/Herald during the opponent's turn for another 2 negates or can be used for more complex combos such as summoning both watapon and lilybell or stuff like that... I used to play a herald synchro deck like that...) -herald of the orange light/the agent - earth (for summoning herald of the arc light/omega or as a hand trap) -the agent of creation - venus (there is an extra link combo with this card, idaten and machine angel absolute ritual) -galaxy soldier (infinity, or pleiades with natasha) -manju -honest -artifact lancea (handtrap in case decks that banish becomes meta) -consecrated light (side deck) -soul of purity and light -ohka -hieratics -brilliant fusion -foolish burial -kaiju/moon mirror shield (in side deck) -shaddoll dragon (beatrice target) -sandaion -time miaden -arch-airknight -phosphorage           ONLY FOR FUN SUGGESTIONS: -more copies of natasha -reasoning -monster gate -rank-up-magic - the seventh one -devirituals + mega zaborg (cannot be searched)/invicil (cannot be searched)/arcana force XXI (50/50 chances)/angel o7/vanity's ruler -goddess of sweet revenge (+fairy tail snow via beatrice) -return of the world (+ritual buster) -urgent ritual art (+ritual buster) -sprite's blessing/advanced ritual art -valkyrie of the nordic ascendant (and odin in the extra deck) -raregold armor (with natasha) -tsukumo slash (with gale dogra) -nephthys the blazing sacred phoenix/double byte dragon (if you really like this kind of cards) -xyz burst -the winged dragon of ra + immortal phoenix (if you go against players that uses sphere mode) -seraph engine (better with brilliant fusion) (YES, is just for fun, it makes the deck a lot more inconsistent!!!) -gateway to chaos -break of the world -chaos zone -mausoleum of the emperor -set rotation -monster reborn -soul charge -fulfillment of the contract -legacy of the duelist -the sanctum of parshath -light of redemption -pot of acquisitiveness -pinpoint landing -ascending soul -ritual cage -photon sanctuary -gracefull queen -vrash -vennu -dakini -tarotrei + cards like pot of the forbidden -master hyperion -arcana force 0 -lee the world chalice fairy -enrise -disserere -demolisher of rituals -breakthrough skill -instant fusion (panzer dragon and natasha into pleiades, detach natasha, etc. etc. etc.) -fusion substitute -number 29 -herald of pure light -ritual of grace -hymn of light -galaxy cyclone -shopina -mozarta -athena -jowgen/aurora paragon/barrier statue of the heavens (+machine angel ritual in grave) -banisher of the radiance -shining angel -nova summoner -nikitama -fluffal angel -super quantal fairy alphan -guiding light -double summon -chain summoning -trial and tribulation -sacred serpent's wake -ritual weapon -grisaille prison

deck_excerpt: Lightsworn Dinosaur Invoked 2018 (Smaller Version of 60 Card Decks)
deck_description: Soooooo after having this crazy theory about making Lightsworns with Dinosaurs and the Invoked engine, I brought it to life! And it's actually kinda meta. I was surprisingly able to beat a tier two deck, Cinderella, and a lot of tier one decks... I was actually able to beat Pure Dinosaurs, ABC Knightmare, and Pure Sky Strikers. The only problem with this deck is that the brick rate is moderate. You can actually draw too many monsters in your starting hand which will then cause you to lose the game. That has always been the problem when you combine multiple archetypes that are somewhat large. This deck is somewhat meta I would say tier 1.5 maybe. But in the worst case, this deck is always super fun to play against your friends as a casual deck. The goal of this deck is to otk your opponent going second or control your opponent with you going first. You pick! You want to simply mill. That is the goal, that way you can trigger cards like Performage Trick Clown, Revival Golem, Wulf, Lightsworn Beast, etc... To special summon from the graveyard so you can make a lot of link monsters or go into Minerva, the Exalted Lightsworn, or PSY-Framelord Omega, or whatever you want to play to make your opponent suffer from your deck being depleted. Double Evolution Pill kills in this deck. Being able to bait your opponent's handtraps with something like normal summoning Aleister The Invoker and then using Double Evolution Pill to get Ultimate Conductor Tyranno is amazing, or the other way around. You can also make Naturia Beast going first sometimes. If you have Giant Rex in your hand and you have Foolish Burial in your hand is you can normal summon Giant Rex and then us Foolish Burial to send Glow-Up Blub and use Glow-Up Blubs effect to send one card from your deck to grave to special summon himself. Then you can go into Naturia Beast which is basically a win condition going first since he stops all spells plus you'd have UCT. There are other ways to make Naturia Beast first turn like using Double Evolution Pill and using Giant Rex in your hand as material plus another card and get UCT and then special summon Giant Rex then you can normal summon Glow-Up Blub from your hand to get Naturia Beast. Enjoy the deck profile and as always if you have any questions or comments please write them down below or message me directly!

deck_excerpt: A Galaxy-Eyes deck based around both Summoning Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon and Xyz Summoning into Galaxy-Eyes Rank 8 Xyz Monsters.
deck_description:
This is my first ever Galaxy-Eyes deck, other than a rather badly failed attempt at a Galaxy-Eyes/Cipher deck, so please don't judge to harshly. As I learn more and more, I hope to keep the deck constantly updated. A few combos that could be exploited in this deck:
  1. Trade-In can send  Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon to the GY to draw 2 cards, them revive with Return of the Dragon Lords. Normal Summon Galaxy Knight using its effect, allowing for an Xyz Summon. If that Xyz Monster would be destroyed, Return of the Dragon Lords can be banished for a 1-time escape.
  2. Galaxy Soldier can send Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon to the GY, and once there Special Summons itself, and search out for Galaxy Knight. With it on the field, you can Normal Summon Galaxy Knight to Special Summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from the GY, for an Xyz Summon.
  3. Photon Sanctuary can be activated in order to Special Summon 2 Photon Tokens, and with them you can Special Summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon. This also leaves you a Normal Summon, and with Galaxy Knight, you can Normal Summon it in order to Xyz Summon.
  I'm afraid these are the only combos I could find, but best of luck to anyone that tries out the deck, and let me know what you think of it!

deck_excerpt: High Consistency Chain Burn Deck. Updated with the most recent ban list in mind. Capable of OTK. You should win about 90% of your duels with this deck
deck_description: Combo 1: When opponent has less then 3 monsters in their main monster zones, activate Just desserts, then chain Ojama Trio to give them 3 Ojama Tokens. Just desserts will then resolve its effect conflicting 1500 damage to your opponent. (Plus 500 x whatever monsters they already have.)  Combo 2: While your opponent has many cards on their field, and you have any combination of Just desserts, Ceasefire, Secret Barrel, or Secret Blast set down on your field, activate them all, and then activate Accumulated Fortunes as the 4th (or higher) chain. You'll do insane Burn damage and draw 2 cards.  Combo 3: Set Absolute King Back Jack face down. When he's (or she... it's 2018 I don't judge) destroyed and sent to the graveyard, activate his effect to change the order of the top 3 cards of your deck. You should pick a normal trap to be on top. Then, banish Absolute King Back Jack to excavate the top card of your deck, and since you already know what you'll get, you should have drawn a normal trap, and since it's a normal trap, you can set it face down on your field as soon as the effect resolves. Choose a different trap depending on the situation.
